<div class="prose">

<h2>The three AI rules</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>AI can help me think — but I do the thinking.</strong> If I couldn't defend an argument in conversation because the AI made it, that argument isn't mine.</li>
  <li><strong>The work I submit is my words, my decisions, my voice.</strong> AI can support drafting, but the deliverable that gets turned in is mine.</li>
  <li><strong>Every time I use AI, I document it.</strong> Tool, prompts, what it did, what I did, OPVL of the AI, one thing it got wrong. No exceptions.</li>
</ol>

<h2>What AI use is encouraged for</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Brainstorming</strong> — generating options, exploring angles you haven't considered, getting unstuck.</li>
  <li><strong>Explaining concepts</strong> in different ways when the textbook didn't click.</li>
  <li><strong>Feedback on your writing</strong> — "is this argument clear? what's missing?"</li>
  <li><strong>Summarising</strong> long documents so you can decide whether to read them in full.</li>
  <li><strong>Translating</strong> — between languages, or between technical and plain-language registers.</li>
  <li><strong>Role-playing</strong> different perspectives so you can stress-test your own.</li>
  <li><strong>Practicing</strong> — defense rehearsal, quick-fire questioning on a topic, Socratic dialogue.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What AI use is NOT allowed</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Generating the deliverable.</strong> The words, code, data, or work you turn in must be yours. If 80% of a paragraph came from an AI, that's the AI's work, not yours.</li>
  <li><strong>Hidden use.</strong> Failing to fill out the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> when AI was used is an academic integrity violation. Honest disclosure → no penalty. Hidden use → escalated consequences.</li>
  <li><strong>Letting AI do the thinking.</strong> If you couldn't defend an argument in conversation because the AI made it, that argument isn't yours and shouldn't be in your work.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Decision examples</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>OK</th><th>Not OK</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Asking Gemini to explain how subduction zones produce tsunamis after the textbook didn't click. Then writing your hazard profile in your own words from notes.</td>
      <td>Asking Gemini to write your hazard profile, then lightly editing it and submitting.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Asking Claude to give you feedback on a draft paragraph: "Is my argument clear? What's missing?" Then revising yourself.</td>
      <td>Asking Claude to rewrite your paragraph to sound better, then pasting its version in.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Using the Engineering Coach AI partner to talk through cost-benefit reasoning before making a sim decision. Documenting the conversation in your engineering journal.</td>
      <td>Asking an AI "what should I do in this sim scenario?" and copying its strategy without testing or thinking.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Submitting AI Documentation alongside your work, even when AI use was minor ("used Gemini to translate one paragraph from Hindi").</td>
      <td>Using AI to draft a section and not mentioning it because "it was just a little bit."</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-title">The disclosure principle</div>
  Disclosure isn't policing. It's a metacognitive habit. The point of filling out the documentation template isn't to get permission — it's to make you notice what the AI did versus what you did. Students who can articulate that distinction learn more from AI than students who can't.
</div>

<h2>If you're unsure</h2>

<p>If you're not sure whether a particular AI use is OK, ask before submitting. The rule of thumb:</p>

<blockquote>"Could I explain to my teacher exactly what I did, and would I be comfortable doing so?"</blockquote>

<p>If yes, you're probably fine and just need to document it. If no, that's a signal to stop and recalibrate before submitting.</p>

</div>
